## Trade Rationale: Bull Call Spread

Good morning. Based on our medium-conviction **Bullish thesis** for the underlying asset, currently trading at $415.72, we are recommending a **Bull Call Spread**. This strategy is a highly effective way to capitalize on a moderate upward move while defining our maximum risk, which is particularly prudent given the current market context of extremely high Implied Volatility (IV Rank: 94.1). While high IV typically favors selling premium, the Bull Call Spread allows us to maintain a bullish directional bias while partially mitigating the cost of the long call by selling the higher-strike call.

The structure of the trade involves buying the **420 Call** and simultaneously selling the **435 Call**. This creates a net debit position, which represents our maximum possible loss. Our maximum profit is capped at the difference between the strikes ($15.00) minus the net debit paid. This spread is designed to profit if the asset moves above the 420 strike, achieving maximum profitability if the price closes at or above $435 by expiration. By utilizing this spread, we are expressing confidence that the price will move up, but we are acknowledging that the move may be limited, making the sale of the 435 Call an efficient way to finance the trade.

The primary risk in this defined-risk strategy is the loss of the entire net premium paid if the stock fails to rise above the long 420 strike. Given the high IV environment, the premium paid for the spread may be elevated, meaning a larger upfront cost is at risk. Furthermore, while the Bull Call Spread aligns perfectly with our bullish directional view, the high IV Rank suggests that the market is pricing in significant movement. If the stock moves aggressively higher, exceeding $435, our profit is capped, and we would miss out on further gains that a simple long call would capture. We will monitor the price action closely, particularly around the 420 strike, as time decay (Theta) will work against this debit spread if the stock remains stagnant.

